Content: "WASHINGTON (Reuters) - Republican President Donald Trump on Tuesday backed tax legislation but rejected efforts to overhaul it, which he criticized in the news media and on television as a 'monster” that would leave big business uncompetitive. The administration is set on rolling new corporate tax and other legislation in a final push to advance a tax package that is expected to be introduced late on Friday, an administration official said. The bill would extend existing tax-cut and eliminate the alternative minimum tax created by the 2001 2001 Democratic-controlled House of Representatives. Its tax plan has not been finalized and has run into questions from several conservative lawmakers.  The House bill would reduce the tax rate on goods and services exported from overseas to 30 percent, the official said.  It would also extend and reduce the corporate tax rate to 20 percent. It contains an increase, if it comes through as it stands, of 20 percent on everything from software to construction products and technology to medical devices, the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.  The bill, which the Senate passed on April 4 by 66-43, will only be written by the House, but not signed by the White House.  ",<|endoftext|>
